{
  "doc_id": "33976",
  "text": "Food quality is understood as good nutritional, microbiological and textural quality [CITATION_1] . Textural quality incorporates the mechanical, geometrical and surface qualities of the product, perceivable through mechanical, tactile and sight and sound receptors, which can be considered to evaluate sensory quality (cf. [CITATION_2] . However, in addition to sensory attributes, as part of PQ, an expected level of safety, utility, cost, etc. must also be present [CITATION_3] , after which it is possible to discuss the overall perceived quality of the product as described above by [CITATION_4] . A similar view, albeit within the framework of differently structured characteristics, was also presented by [CITATION_5] .",
